<chapter xml:id="ch-maxmin" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Finding Maxima and Minima</title>


<section xml:id="sec_understandingextrema">
	<title>Finding Local Extrema</title>
	
	<p>
		In any economic system, and in any business, there are <em>many</em> different choices you can make.
		Of these choices, some are better than others.  
	</p>
	<p>
		Ideally, you will want to make the <em>best</em> choice. 
		In practice, limits on resources and time often limit the amount of change that is feasible. 
		In these cases, you want to make the <em>locally optimal</em> choice -- the choice that is better than all the alternatives that are "nearby" to your current location.
	</p>

	<p>
		Part of the complexity of economic systems are the  large number of variables and different ways of comparing which options are "better." 
		In this course, we will focus on functions of a single variable, and we will always compare the magnitude of the outputs. 
	</p>
	<p>
		To help define our terms precisely, we will start with a more concrete, physical example.
	</p>

	
	<exploration xml:id="explore_introducemaxmin">
