		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					At which values does <m>f</m> have a <em>local/relative maximum</em>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The graph has local maxima at <m>x=-1</m> and <m>x=3</m>, because <m>f</m> has <em></em>
				</p>
				<p>
					These are local maxima because if you imagine standing on the graph at those points, moving left or right will <em>decrease</em> your height. 
				</p>
				<p>
					Said another way, there is a local maxima because when you read the graph from left to right, these are the <m>x</m>-values where the graph looks like <m>\nearrow\, \searrow</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					At which values does <m>f</m> have a <em>local/relative minimum</em>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The graph has a local minimum at <m>x=-2</m>, <m>x=1</m>, or <m>x=4</m>
				</p>
				<p>
					These are local minima because if you imagine standing on the graph at those points, moving left or right will <em>increase</em> your height. 
				</p>
				<p>
					Said another way, there is a local minima because when you read the graph from left to right, these are the <m>x</m>-values where the graph looks like <m>\searrow\, \nearrow</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					At which values does <m>f</m> have a <em>absolute/global maximum</em>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The graph has a global maximum of <m>y=4</m> at <m>x=3</m>
				</p>
				<p>
					These is a global maximum because if you imagine standing on the graph at those points, there is <em>no way place you could to move to to increase your height</em>. 
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					At which values does <m>f</m> have a <em>absolute/global minimum</em>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The graph has a global minimum of <m>y=-1</m> at <m>x=-2</m>
				</p>
				<p>
					These is a global maximum because if you imagine standing on the graph at those points, there is <em>no way place you could to move to to decrease your height</em>. 
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
	</exploration>

	<p>
		In the exercise above, there are three special kinds of points that mostly (but do not exactly) correspond to locations of maxima and minima:
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					The curve <m>y=f</m> is <em>horizontal</em> at <m>x=-1,1,2</m>.
				 
				</p>
				<p>
					This is because <m>f'(x)=0</m> at these points. 
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The curve <m>y=f</m> is has a <em>singularity</em> at <m>x=3</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					This is because <m>f'(x)=DNE</m> at this points.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The curve <m>y=f</m> is has an <em>endpoint</em> at <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=4</m>. 
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</p>

	<theorem xml:id="thm-maxminonlyat">
		<statement>
			<p>
				A function <m>f</m> can <em>only</em> have a maxima or minima at <m>x=a</m> if one of the following are true 
				<ol>
					<li>
						<p>
							<m>f</m> is horizontal at <m>a</m>.  This happens when <m>f'=0</m>.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							<m>f</m> has a singularity at <m>a</m>.  This happens when <m>f'\ DNE</m>.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							<m>a</m> is an endpoint of the height function <m>f</m>.
						</p>
					</li>
				</ol>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</theorem>

	<p>
		The values of <m>x</m> where <m>f'(x)=0</m> or <m>f'(x)\ DNE</m> are called the <term>critical points</term> of <m>f</m>.  
		This is because finding these points is one of the most important steps when you are looking for the maxima and minima of the function <m>f</m>. 
	</p>
	
	<p>
		<alert>Warning:</alert> Not every critical point is a maxima or minima. 
		In <xref ref="fig_maxminintroimage"/>, <m>2</m> is a critical point of <m>f</m> because <m>f'(2)=0</m>, and so the function is horizontal at <m>x=2</m>.  However, <m>x=2</m> is <em>not</em> a local maxima or minima, since you can increase your height by moving right and decrease it by moving left. 
	</p>
	<p>
		To be able to check if a point is indeed a maxima or minima, we need a more precise definition.
	</p>
	<definition xml:id="def-localmaximin">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Let <m>f</m> be a function which is continuous at <m>x=a</m>. 
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>f</m> has a <term>local maxima</term> at <m>x=a</m> if the graph goes from increasing to decreasing at <m>a</m> (the function looks like <m>\nearrow\,\searrow</m> at <m>a</m>).
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>f</m> has a <term>local minima</term> at <m>x=a</m> if the graph goes from decreasing to increasing at <m>a</m> (the function looks like <m>\searrow\,\nearrow</m> at <m>a</m>).
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>f</m> has an <term>extrema</term> at <m>x=a</m> if there is either a maxima or minima at <m>x=a</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<theorem xml:id="thm-increasingfunction">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>f</m> is a differentiable function at <m>x</m>
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						height <m>f</m> is increasing (<m>\,\nearrow\,</m>) at <m>x</m> <em>if and only if</em> the slope <m>f'(x)</m> is positive <m>(+)</m>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						height <m>f</m> is decreasing (<m>\,\searrow\,</m>) at <m>x</m> <em>if and only if</em> the slope <m>f'(x)</m> is positive <m>(-)</m>
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</statement>
	</theorem>

	<p>
		In <xref ref="explore_introducemaxmin"/>, the function <m>f</m> is increasing  on the interval <m>(-2,-1) \cup (1,2)\cup (2,3)</m> <em>because</em> <m>f'</m> is positive on that interval. 
	</p>
	
	<exploration xml:id="ex_maxminexample1">
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Let <m>f(x) = \dfrac{-x^3}{3} + x + 1</m>
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the critical points of <m>f</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Recall that the <em>critical points</em> of <m>f</m> are the <m>x</m> values where  <m>f'(x) =0</m> or <m>f'(x) \ DNE</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					To find when <m>f'=0</m> or <m>f'\ DNE</m>, we must first find an equation for the derivative <m>f'</m>. 
					<md>
						<mrow> f'(x) = \amp \ddx{ \frac{-1}{3} x^3 + x + 1  } </mrow>
						<mrow>= \amp \ddx{ \frac{-1}{3} x^3 } + \ddx{x} + \ddx{1} </mrow>
						<mrow>= \amp \frac{-1}{3} \ddx{x^3} + 1 + 0</mrow>
						<mrow>= \amp \frac{-1}{3}\cdot 3x^2 + + 1</mrow>
						<mrow>= \amp -x^2 + 1</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					To find when <m>f'=0</m>, simply solve the equation 
					<me>
						-x^2 + 1 = 0
					</me>
					Solve the equation by factoring.
					It is easier to factor equations when the highest power term has a factor of 1.  To do this, multiply both sides of the equation by -1, simplifying, and factoring
					<md>
						<mrow>(-1) \cdot (-x^2 + 1) \amp =(-1) \cdot = 0 </mrow>
						<mrow>x^2 - 1 \amp = 0 </mrow>
						<mrow>(x+1) (x-1) \amp  = 0</mrow>
					</md>
					The only way this can happen is if either the first or second terms equal 0.  In other words, solve 
					<md>
						<mrow> x+1 = 0 \amp \text{ or } \amp x-1=0 </mrow>
						<mrow>x = -1 \amp \text{ or } \amp x=1</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					We have a singularity when <m>f'\ DNE</m>.  
					Looking at the graph of <m>f</m>, it does not look like there are any singularities.  
				</p>
				<p>
					Looking at the function, the derivative <m>f'(x) = -x^2+1</m> is always defined. 
					This confirms that this function <m>f</m> does not have any singularities.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use a calculator to find the local extrema for <m>f</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Graphing the function we see

					<image width="50%" xml:id="img_maxminexample1graphed">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[axes] (-2,0)--(2,0) ; 
								\draw[axes] (0,-2)--(0,2);
								\draw [domain=-1.5:1.5] plot ({\x},{ (-1/3)*(\x)^3 + \x + 1 });
								\draw[red,dashed] (0.8,5/3)--(1.2,5/3);
								\draw[red,dashed] (-0.8,1/3)--(-1.2,1/3);
								\draw[blue,dotted](1,5/3)--(1,0) node[below] {$x=1$};
								\draw[blue,dotted](-1,1/3)--(-1,0) node[below] {$x=-1$};
								\draw[blue] (1,{5/3}) circle (2pt);
								\draw[blue] (-1,{1/3}) circle (2pt);
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>		
					</image>
				</p>
				<p>
					Looking at the graph, we can see that there is a local maxima at <m>x=1</m> and a local minima at <m>x=-1</m>. 
					We also know that there are no other locations where there <em>might</em> be a maxima or minima, even off the screen of the calculator.
				</p>
				<p>
					In particular, this tells us that there are <em>no</em> absolute maxima or minima. 
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the first derivative to find the local extrema for <m>f</m>.
					Find the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and when it is decreasing. 
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					We are asked to locate the maxima and minima without looking at the graph of the function. 
				</p>
				<p>
					The <em>key idea</em> is that we can use  the derivative function <m>f'</m> to make a very rough sketch of the function by using <xref ref="thm-increasingfunction"/>.  
				</p>
				<p>
					We have already used <m>f'</m> to find all values of <m>x</m> where <m>f'=0</m> or <m>f'\ DNE</m>. 
					To make our sketch <alert>plot these points on a number line</alert>.  
				</p>
				<p>
					<image width="50%" xml:id="image_maxminexample1_signchartv1">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
								\def\xval{-1} \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{ 1} \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>						
					</image>
				</p>
				<p>
					Next, we must compute the derivative <m>f'</m> to the left and right of each of the points above.  
					There are three intervals: to the left of -1, between -1 and 1, and to the right of 1.  You can chose any number in those intervals.
					<dl>
						<li>
							<title>left of -1</title>
							<m>f'(-2) = -(-2)^2 + 1 = -3 = (-)</m>
						</li>
						<li>
							<title>between -1 and 1</title>
							<m>f'(0) = -(0)^2 + 1 = 1 = (+)</m>
						</li>
						<li>
							<title>right of -1</title>
							<m>f'(2) = -(2)^2 + 1 = -3 = (-)</m>
						</li>
					</dl>
					Mark the magnitude of the derivative below the interval, and draw an <m>\nearrow</m> or <m>\searrow</m> above the line to indicate the behavior of the function.
				</p>
				<p>
					<image width="50%" xml:id="image_maxminexample1_signchartv2">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
								\def\xval{-1} \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{ 1} \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{-2} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(-)$};
														\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\searrow$};
								\def\xval{0} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(+)$};
														\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
								\def\xval{2} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(-)$};
														\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\searrow$};
									
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>						
					</image>
				</p>
				<p>
					This sign chart is a very rough sketch of the function, but it is complete enough to show that there is a local minima at <m>x=-1</m> (due to the <m>\searrow\,\nearrow</m>) and that there is a local maxima at <m>x=1</m> (due to the <m>\nearrow\,\searrow</m>).
				</p>
				<p>
					It is also clear from the sign chart that the function is increasing on the interval between -1 and 1.  In interval notation, it is increasing on the interval <m>(-1,1)</m>
				</p>
				<p>
					The function is decreasing on two intervals: to the left of -1 and to the right of 1.  In interval notation, <m>f</m> is decreasing on the interval <m>(-\infty, -1)\cup (1,\infty)</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
	</exploration>

	<assemblage xml:id="assemblage-maxminmethod">
		<title>A Strategy for Finding Extrema </title>
		<p>
			Let <m>f</m> be any function which is continuous on an open interval. To find the local extrema, 
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Use the derivative function <m>f'</m> to find where <m>f'=0</m> and when <m>f'\ DNE</m>.
						<ul>
							<li>
								<p>
									<em>Polynomials:</em> factor to find the 0's. 
								</p>
							</li>
							<li>
								<p>
									<em>Fractions:</em> <m>\dfrac{A}{B}</m> is equal to zero if when <m>A=0</m> and <m>B\neq 0</m>.  
														<m>\dfrac{A}{B}</m> is undefined when <m>B=0</m>. 
								</p>
							</li>
						</ul>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Plot these points on a number line.  
						This cuts the real numbers into several intervals.
					</p>
					<p>
						Use a closed dot for <m>f'=0</m> and an open circle for <m>f'\ DNE</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Compute <m>f'</m> on each of the intervals you have found above. 
						Mark whether <m>f'</m> is <m>(+)</m> or <m>(-)</m> below the interval, and draw <m>\nearrow</m> or <m>\searrow</m> above the interval.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p> 
						Read off the answer to the question, using your sign chart as a very rough sketch of the function. 
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
	</assemblage>

	<exploration xml:id="ex_maxminexample2">
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Let <m>f(x) = \dfrac{-x^4}{4} + \frac{8}{3}x^3 + 4</m>
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and decreasing..
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					First, we must find the critical points. 
					In other words, find the <m>x</m> such that <m>f'(x) =0</m> or <m>f'(x) \ DNE</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					First, find an equation for the derivative <m>f'</m>, and factor it. 
					<md>
						<mrow> f'(x) = \amp \ddx{ \frac{-1}{4} x^4 + \frac{8}{3} x^3 + 4   } </mrow>
						<mrow>  = \amp \frac{-1}{4}\cdot 4x^3 + \frac{8}{3} \cdot 3x^2 + 0 </mrow>
						<mrow>  = \amp -x^3 + 8x^2</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					To find when <m>f'=0</m>, simply solve the equation 
					<me>
						  -x^3 + 8x^2     = 0
					</me>
					Solve the equation by factoring.
					It is easier to factor equations when the highest power term has a factor of 1.  
					To do this, factor out a <m>-x^2</m> from both terms
					<md>
						<mrow>(-x^2) \cdot (x - 8) \amp =  0 </mrow>
					</md>
					The only way this can happen is if either the first or second terms equal 0.  In other words, solve 
					<md>
						<mrow> x = 0 \amp \text{ or } \amp x-8=0 </mrow>
						<mrow> x = 0 \amp \text{ or } \amp x=8   </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					We have a singularity when <m>f'\ DNE</m>.  
					Looking at the graph of <m>f</m>, it does not look like there are any singularities.  
				</p>
				<p>
					Looking at the function, the derivative <m>f'(x) = -x^2(x-8)</m> is always defined. 
					This confirms that this function <m>f</m> does not have any singularities.
				</p>
				<p>
					To find when the function is increasing and decreasing without looking at the graph of the function, we must use  the derivative function <m>f'</m> to make a very rough sketch of the function by using <xref ref="thm-increasingfunction"/>.  
					We will do this by making the sign chart of <m>f'</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					<image width="40%" xml:id="image_maxminexample2_signchartv1">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-2,0) -- (12,0);
