	<p>
		We now have a precise, repeatable strategy for finding maxima and minima. 
		The following definition and theorem make this strategy precise. 
	</p>
	<definition xml:id="def-criticalpoints">
		<statement>
			<p>
				The <term>critical numbers</term> of <m>f</m> are the numbers <m>c</m> such that <m></m>
				<dl>
					<li>
						<title>Both</title>
						<p>
							<m>f(c)</m> is defined
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<title>And</title>
						<p>
							<dl>
								<li>
									<title>either</title>
									<m>f'(c) = 0</m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<title>or</title>
									<m>f'(c)\ DNE</m>
								</li>
							</dl>
						</p>
					</li>
				</dl>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<theorem xml:id="thm-firstderivativetest">
		<title>The First Derivative Test</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>c</m> is a critical number of a function <m>f</m>. 
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						<em>If</em> <m>f'</m> goes from <m>(+)</m> to <m>(-)</m> at <m>c</m> (<m>f</m> goes from <m>\nearrow</m> to <m>\searrow</m>)
						<em>then</em> <m>f</m> has a local <em>maximum</em> at <m>c</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<em>If</em> <m>f'</m> goes from <m>(-)</m> to <m>(+)</m> at <m>c</m> (<m>f</m> goes from <m>\searrow</m> to <m>\nearrow</m>)
						<em>then</em> <m>f</m> has a local <em>minimum</em> at <m>c</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						If <m>f'</m> does not change sign at <m>c</m> (if <m>f</m> goes <m>\searrow\,\searrow</m> or <m>\nearrow\,\nearrow</m>),
						<em>then</em> <m>f</m> does <em>not</em> have a local maximum or minimum at <m>c</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</statement>
	</theorem>
	
	<p>
		In some cases, we will have more knowledge about the derivative <m>f'</m> than we have about the height function.  
		The key thing to notice is that we have been using the <em>slope function <m>f'</m> </em> to teach us about the <em>height function <m>f</m></em>. 
	</p>
	
	<exploration xml:id="ex_maxminexample3">
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>f(x)</m> is an uknown (or mystery) position function, with known derivative function 
				<me>
					f'(x) = \dfrac{(x+3)e^x}{(x-2)^2}
				</me>
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and decreasing. 
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					In this example, we are <em>given</em> a factored version of the derivative <m>f'</m>, so we do not need to use any of our rules.
				</p>
				<p>
					Next, we must find the points where <m>f'=0</m> or <m>f'\ DNE</m>.  Recall that a fraction <m>\dfrac{A}{B}=0</m> if and only if <m>A=0</m>, and <m>\dfrac{A}{B}\ DNE</m> if and only if <m>B=0</m>.  We must therefore solve two equations.
				</p>
				<p>
					For the first,
					<md>
						<mrow>f' = \amp 0</mrow>
						<mrow>(x+3)e^x \amp =0</mrow>
					</md>
					Because <m>e^x \neq 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, this can only happen if <m>x+3=0</m>, which means when <m>x=-3</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					For the second, 
					<md>
						<mrow>f' \amp DNE </mrow>
						<mrow>(x-2^2) \amp =0 </mrow>
						<mrow>x-2 \amp =0</mrow>
						<mrow>x \amp = 2</mrow>
					</md>
					Plotting these on a number line, we get 
					<image xml:id="image_maxminexample3_signchartv1">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-5,0) -- (5,0);
								\def\xval{2 } \draw[fill=white] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{-3 } \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>						
					</image>
				</p>
				<p>
					Recall that we were <em>given</em> the derivative function, which we now use to check the sign of each interal.  
					We can either use a calculator as before
					<md>
						<mrow>f'(-4) \amp  = \dfrac{(-4+3)e^{-4}}{(-4-2)^2} = \dots = (-)</mrow>
						<mrow>f'(0) \amp = \dfrac{(0+3)e^0}{(0-2)^2} = \dots = (+)</mrow>
						<mrow>f'(3) \amp = \dfrac{(3+3)e^3}{(3-2)^2} = \dots = (+)</mrow>
					</md>
					or we can do basic "sign arithmetic" in our head
					<md>
						<mrow>f'(-4) \amp  = \dfrac{(-)(+))}{(-)^2} = \frac{(-)}{(+)} =  (-)</mrow>
						<mrow>f'(0) \amp = \dfrac{(+)(+)}{(-)^2} = \frac{(+)}{(+)} = (+)</mrow>
						<mrow>f'(3) \amp = \dfrac{(+)(+))}{(+)^2} = (+)</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					Either way, we obtain 
					<image xml:id="image_maxminexample3_signchartv2">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-5,0) -- (5,0);
								\def\xval{2 } \draw[fill=white] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{-3 } \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};


								\def\xval{-4} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(-)$};
														\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\searrow$};
								\def\xval{0} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(+)$};
														\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
								\def\xval{3} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(+)$};
														\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>						
					</image>
				</p>
				<p>
					Reading off of the sign chart for <m>f'</m>, we see that the <em>original</em> (mystery) function <m>f</m> is increasing on the intervals <m>(-3,2)\cup(2,\infty)</m>, and the <em>original</em> (mystery) function <m>f</m> is decreasing on the interval <m>(-\infty,-3)</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the <m>x</m> values of all relative extrema. 
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Using the sign chart for <m>f'</m>, we see that there is a local minima at <m>x=-3</m>, and there is no local maxima.
				</p>
				<p>
					<alert>Aside:</alert> Note that the something very strange happens at <m>x=-2</m>.  With a little more information about the original function, we would learn that <m>f</m> is undefined at <m>x=-2</m> and therefore could not be an extrema regardless of the sign chart.  However, these details are beyond the scope of this course, and won't come up in any of our examples.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
	</exploration>
		
	<exercise xml:id="ex_maxminexample4">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Find all maxima and minima for the function 
				<me>
					f(x) = \dfrac{x^2 + 1}{x}
				</me>
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				First, we must find an equation for <m>f'</m>.
				<me>
					f'(x) = \ddxfrac{\dfrac{ \red{x^2 + 1} }{\blue{x}}} 
				</me>
				We are taking the derivative of a fraction, so we must use the quotient rule <m>\D{\frac{t}{b}} = \frac{b\cdot t' - t\cdot b'}{b^2}</m>
				<md>
					<mrow>f'(x)  \amp = \dfrac{\blue{x}\D{\red{x^2+1}} - \red{(x^2+1)}\D{\blue{x}} }{(\blue{x})^2}</mrow>
					<mrow>		 \amp = \dfrac{\blue{x} (\red{2x+0}) - \red{(x^2+1)}\blue{1} }{(\blue{x})^2}</mrow>
					<mrow>		 \amp = \dfrac{ 2x^2 - x^2 - 1 }{x^2}</mrow>
					<mrow>		 \amp = \dfrac{ x^2 - 1 }{x^2}</mrow>
					<mrow> 		 \amp = \dfrac{(x+1)(x-1)}{x^2}</mrow>
				</md>
				
				Next, we must find all values of <m>x</m> such that <m>f'=0</m> and <m>f'\ DNE</m>.
				<md>
					<mrow>f' \amp =0 </mrow>
					<mrow>(x+1)(x-1) \amp =0</mrow>
					<mrow>x=1,-1 </mrow>
				</md>
				similarly 
				<md>
					<mrow>f' \amp DNE</mrow>
					<mrow>x \amp =0</mrow>
				</md>
				Plotting these on the number line gives
			</p>
			<p>
				<image width="75%" xml:id="image_maxminexample4_signchartv1">
					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}
							\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
							\def\xval{-1 } \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
							\def\xval{0 } \draw[fill=white] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
							\def\xval{1 } \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
						\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>						
				</image>
			</p>
			<p>
				Evaluating <m>f' = \frac{x^2-1}{x^2}</m> on each of these intervals gives 
				<image width="75%" xml:id="image_maxminexample4_signchartv2">
					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}
							\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
							\def\xval{-1 } \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
							\def\xval{0 } \draw[fill=white] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
							\def\xval{1 } \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};

							\def\xval{-2} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'=(+)$}; \node[red] at (\xval,0.4){\large $\nearrow$};
							\def\xval{-0.66} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'=(-)$}; \node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\searrow$};
							\def\xval{0.66} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'=(-)$}; \node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
							\def\xval{2} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'=(-)$}; \node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
						\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>						
				</image>
			</p>
			<p>
				The function has a local <em>maxima</em> at <m>x=-1</m> and a local <em>minima</em> at <m>x=1</m>
			</p>
			<p>
				Note again that the orignal function is undefined (<m>DNE</m>) at <m>x=0</m>, so <m>x=0</m> cannot be a max or a min regardless of the sign chart. 
			</p>
		</solution>
	</exercise>

	<p>
		As we have seen, the steps in every max/min problem are the same 
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					Find an equation for <m>f'</m> (if you are not already given it)
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Solve <m>f'=0</m>
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Solve <m>f'\ DNE</m>
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Make the sign chart for <m>f'</m>
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Read off the answer.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</p>

</section>

<section xml:id="sec_absolutemaxmin">
	<title>Finding Absolute Extrema</title>

	<p>
		In this class, we focus on local maxima and minima because of their close connections to calculus and their applications to marginal profit. 
		But in many cases, global (also called absolute) maxima and minima are often of much greater interest. 
		To see why, we begin with one more example. 
	</p>
	
	<exploration xml:id="ex_maxminexample5">
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>P(x) = x^3 - 6x^2 + 9x +10 </m> is a total profit function. 
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the quantities where all local maximum and minimum profits occur. 
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					First, find the marginal profit function 
					<md>
						<mrow>P'(x) \amp  = \ddx{x^3 - 6x^2 + 9x +10 } </mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \ddx{x^3} - \ddx{ 6x^2 } + \ddx{ 9x } + \ddx{10}</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = 3x^2 - 6\cdot 2x^1 + 9 + 0</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = 3x^2 - 12x + 9</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					Next, find when <m>P'=0</m> or <m>P'\ DNE</m>
					<md>
						<mrow>P' \amp = 0</mrow>
						<mrow>3x^2 - 12x + 9 \amp =0</mrow>
						<mrow>3(x^2 - 4x + 3) \amp =0</mrow>
						<mrow>3(x-3)(x-1) \amp =0</mrow>
					</md>
					This happens if and only if <m>x=3</m> or <m>x=1</m>, so these are the locations of the horizontal tangents.  
				</p>
				<p>
					On the other hand, because <m>P'</m> is a polynomial, it is always defined.  Therfore, <m>P'</m> does not have any sigular points. 
				</p>
				<p>
					Making a sign chart as usual gives 
					<image width="50%" xml:id="image_maxminexample5_signchartv2">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[latex-latex, very thick] (-1,0) -- (5,0);
								\def\xval{ 3} \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{ 1} \draw[fill] (\xval,0) circle (2pt) node [below] {$\xval$};
								\def\xval{0} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(+)$};
									\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
								\def\xval{2} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(-)$};
									\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\searrow$};
								\def\xval{4} \draw[stealth-,double,red] (\xval,-0.25) -- (\xval,-0.75) node[below] {\scriptsize $f'(\xval)=(+)$};
									\node[red] at (\xval,0.4) {\large $\nearrow$};
									
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>						
					</image>
				</p>
				<p>
					According to this analysis, a local maximum of profit occurs at <m>x=1</m>, and a local minimum occurs at <m>x=3</m>.  
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If you were able to decide how many items to sell, should you sell 1 item, 3 items, 10 items, or 100 items?				
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The easiest way to answer this question is to compute the total profit from each of the number of items given:
					<md>
						<mrow>P(1) \amp = (1)^3 - 6(1)^2 + 9(1) + 10 = 14</mrow>
						<mrow>P(3) \amp = (3)^3 - 6(3)^2 + 9(3) + 10 = 10</mrow>
						<mrow>P(10) \amp = (10)^3 - 6(10)^2 + 9(10) + 10 = 500</mrow>
						<mrow>P(100) \amp = (100)^3 - 6(100)^2 + 9(100) + 10 = 940,910</mrow>
					</md>
					Clearly, if you are given these options you should sell 100 items and make a total profit of $940,910
				</p>
			</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use your work above to sketch the total profit function.  Use this graph to explain how to decide how many items you should sell. 
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p> 
					Graphing total profit shows that although the function decreases between <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=3</m>, the function rapidly increases after <m>x=3</m> and then proceeds to grow without bound. 
					In other words, you should always sell as many items as possible.
				</p>
				<p>
					<image width="50%" xml:id="image_maxminexample5_sketch">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}[yscale=0.15]
