	</definition>
	
	<theorem xml:id="thm-absoluteextrema">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>f</m> is a function restricted to the closed interval <m>[l,r]</m>. 
				This restriction of <m>f</m> can have an absolute maxima or minima only at 
				<ul>
					<li>
						<p>
							one of the endpoints (<m>l</m> or <m>r</m>)
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							a horiziontal tangent (a point <m>c</m> where <m>f'(c)=0</m>)
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							a singularity (a point <m>c</m> where <m>f'(c)\ DNE</m>).
						</p>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</theorem>

	<p>
		That means that to find <em>all</em> of the absolute extrema for <m>f</m> on a closed interval, it sufficies to find the three kinds of <em>possible</em> locations listed above, and then to compare the <em>height</em> of <m>f</m> at each of these points. 
	</p>
	<assemblage xml:id="assemblage-absolutemaxmin">
		<title>Finding Absolute Extrema</title>
		<p>
			Suppose you are given a height function <m>f</m>.  
			To find the absolute maximum height and minimum height of <m>f</m> on the interval <m>[l,r]</m>,
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Find the derivative (slope) function <m>f'(x)</m>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Find all critical points <m>c</m> where <m>f'(c) = 0</m> (horizontal tangents) or <m>f'(c)\ DNE</m> (singluar points).
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Find the height of the function at each of the critical points <m>c</m>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Find the height of the function at the two endpoints (find <m>f(l)</m> and <m>f(r)</m>).
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
		<p>
			The above computation will give you things like <m>P(c_1) = y_1</m>, <m>P(c_2) = y_2</m>, <m>\dots</m>. 
			If <m>y_2</m> were the largest of all the <m>y</m> values, it would be the <term>absolute maximum</term> profit, and it would occur at quanitity <m>x_2</m>
			If <m>y_3</m> were the least of all the <m>y</m> values, it would be the <term>absolute minimum</term> profit, and it would occur at quanitity <m>x_3</m>.
		</p>
	</assemblage>
	

	<exploration xml:id="ex_maxminexample6">
